  "prompt": "How and when ISS was send to space?",
  "response": "The International Space Station (ISS) is a multi-national collaborative project involving space agencies such as NASA (United States), Roscosmos (Russia), ESA (European Space Agency), JAXA (Japan), and CSA (Canada). Here\u2019s an overview of how and when the ISS was launched into space:\n\n### Concept and Planning\n- The concept for the ISS began in the 1980s as various nations recognized the need for a permanent human presence in low Earth orbit for scientific research, technology development, and international cooperation in space exploration.\n- The first formal discussions began in the early 1990s, leading to agreements among the participating countries.\n\n### Assembly in Space\n- The ISS was assembled in space over a period of several years, with multiple modules launched separately and assembled in orbit.\n\n### Key Launches\n1. **Zarya Module (Functional Cargo Block)**: \n   - Launched on November 20, 1998, by a Russian Proton rocket. This was the first module of the ISS and provided power and storage.\n\n2. **Unity Module (Node 1)**: \n   - Launched on December 4, 1998, by the Space Shuttle Endeavour (STS-88). This module connected American and Russian sections of the station.\n\n3. **Additional Modules**: \n   - Over the years, numerous modules and components were added, including the Zvezda Service Module (July 12, 2000), the Destiny Laboratory (February 24, 2001), and the Japanese Kibo Module (launched in parts between 2008 and 2009), among others.\n\n4. **End of Assembly**: \n   - The main structure of the ISS was completed in 2011, but ongoing modifications and enhancements have continued.\n\n### Continuous Human Presence\n- The first long-term crew arrived at the ISS in November 2000, and since then, the station has maintained a continuous human presence in space.\n\n### Current Status\n- As of late 2023, the ISS remains a significant hub for scientific research and international collaboration in space exploration.\n\nThe ISS has become an iconic symbol of international cooperation in space science and has played a crucial role in expanding our understanding of life in microgravity and other scientific disciplines.",
